<subSubSection id="C375A0EEFFEE37578EAEFCEEFEB2FA86" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BD0F365FFEE37578EAEFCEEFEB2FA86" blockId="6.[151,1437,823,1463]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="B91B2F77FFEE37578EAEFCEEFE9BFCD5" bold="true" box="[199,321,859,884]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The only aphrophorine spittlebug in the new world with a median carina on the face. Crown declivous; face more or less carinate on midline, at least on lower half of frons; head much narrower than pronotum; antennal ledges finely unicarinate; frons with low, rounded median ridge; clypellus tip narrow, extending between fore coxae; lora discoid; genae strongly constricted next to widest part of lora, broad below; rostrum extending to mesocoxae, or to mesotrochanters in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F88E6FFEE37578D3EFC58FB82FBA5" authority="Walker" authorityName="Walker" box="[855,1112,1004,1028]" class="Insecta" family="Aphrophoridae" genus="Aphrophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siccifolia">
<emphasis id="B91B2F77FFEE37578D3EFC58FC3FFBA5" box="[855,997,1004,1028]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">C. siccifolia</emphasis>
(Walker)
</taxonomicName>
. Pronotum with shallow to prominent median fossa near fore border. Tegmina strongly narrowed to obliquely truncate tips. 
<collectingCountry id="F378B3F5FFEE37578AB7FBBAFACCFB86" box="[1246,1302,1039,1063]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Hind</collectingCountry>
wings with circumambient vein sinuate at end of each cell between Cu 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578D2DFBF6FC96FBF0" box="[836,844,1091,1105]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="1.0">1</number>
and vannal fold (
<figureCitation id="1354EFE0FFEE37578A72FB81FBB8FBED" box="[1051,1122,1076,1100]" captionStart="FIGURES 3 – 4" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1704,1727]" captionTargetBox="[175,1408,326,1677]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[169,1419,317,1697]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 3 – 4. Morphology of head (3) and wings (4) of Ptyelini. 3 A. face of Cephisus sanguisuga, holotype; 3 B. head and pronotum, ventrolateral aspect, of C. xanthocephala, holotype; 3 C. head and propleuron of unidentified Cercopinae; 4 A. tegmen of C. siccifolia, ventral aspect showing ventral flange (“ Sc ” of authors); 4 B. hindwing of same; 4 C. same, of Ptyelus sp.; 4 D. same, of Eulepyronia grossa Schmidt, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282463/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578A3BFB81FBB8FBED" box="[1106,1122,1076,1100]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
B). 
<collectingCountry id="F378B3F5FFEE37578AE4FB81FB1FFBED" box="[1165,1221,1076,1100]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Hind</collectingCountry>
tibiae each with a double pecten of 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578F0AFBEFFE72FBD3" box="[355,424,1114,1138]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="14.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="14.0">14–15</number>
black-tipped spines; basal tarsomeres each with 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578D8AFBEFFC2BFBD3" box="[995,1009,1114,1138]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="1.0">1</number>
pecten row of 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578ACEFBEFFB0BFBD3" box="[1191,1233,1114,1138]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6–7</number>
such spines; 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578B1BFBEFFAA5FBD3" box="[1394,1407,1114,1138]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="2.0">2</number>
nd tarsomeres each with 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578FFFFBCAFE1AFB36" box="[406,448,1151,1175]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="8.0" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="7.0">7–9</number>
tiny spines set in deeply V-notched border. Male anal tube surmounted by hoodlike articulated base (
<figureCitation id="1354EFE0FFEE37578F31FB17FE47FB1B" box="[344,413,1186,1210]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1877,1900]" captionTargetBox="[221,1369,524,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[217,1369,519,1863]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 15. Male genitalia of Ptyelini in lateral aspect (A), caudal aspect of theca (B) and widest aspect of style (C). 5. genital capsule of Ptyelus; 6. same, of Cephisus; 7. syntype male of C. sanguisuga; 8. C. diminutus, holotype; 9. C. laticeps, holotype; 10. C. xanthocephala; 11. C. magnificus, holotype; 12. C. variolosus; 13. C. siccifolia; 14. C. jacobii; 15. C. brevipennis, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282464/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578FE7FB17FE47FB1B" box="[398,413,1186,1210]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
A); segment X very short; subgenital plates truncate; styles very large, with long setae on inner faces, apices with tiny process on caudal margin and large dorsal process hooked mesad (
<figureCitation id="1354EFE0FFEE37578AACFB72FAE2FB7E" box="[1221,1336,1223,1247]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1877,1900]" captionTargetBox="[221,1369,524,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[217,1369,519,1863]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 15. Male genitalia of Ptyelini in lateral aspect (A), caudal aspect of theca (B) and widest aspect of style (C). 5. genital capsule of Ptyelus; 6. same, of Cephisus; 7. syntype male of C. sanguisuga; 8. C. diminutus, holotype; 9. C. laticeps, holotype; 10. C. xanthocephala; 11. C. magnificus, holotype; 12. C. variolosus; 13. C. siccifolia; 14. C. jacobii; 15. C. brevipennis, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282464/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
Figs 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578A97FB72FAE2FB7E" box="[1278,1336,1223,1247]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="11.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="7.0">7–15</number>
</figureCitation>
C); theca long, curved caudad, armed with 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578C70FB5FFDFDFAA3" box="[537,551,1258,1282]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="2.0">2</number>
long spines, mesal pair retrorse, lateral pair divergent or curled around shaft (Figs (
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578E88FABAFEC2FA86" box="[225,280,1295,1319]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="10.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="6.0">6–15</number>
)A–B).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C375A0EEFFEE37578EAEFA86FE1FFA16" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD0F365FFEE37578EAEFA86FE1FFA16" blockId="6.[151,1437,823,1463]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis id="B91B2F77FFEE37578EAEFA86FEE1FAEA" bold="true" box="[199,315,1331,1355]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Remarks.</emphasis>
Similar to the Old World genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F88E6FFEE37578CAAFA86FCB4FAEA" box="[707,878,1331,1355]" class="Insecta" family="Aphrophoridae" genus="Cnemidanomia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91B2F77FFEE37578CAAFA86FCB4FAEA" box="[707,878,1331,1355]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Cnemidanomia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but face medially carinate, body broader, with pronotum distinctly wider than head (
<figureCitation id="1354EFE0FFEE37578C20FAE2FD4AFACE" box="[585,656,1367,1391]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,928,951]" captionTargetBox="[217,1369,193,906]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[217,1369,193,907]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Head and pronotum, dorsolateral (perpendicular) aspect. A. C. laticeps, holotype; B. C. siccifolia; C. C. sanguisuga from Amazonian basin; D-F. C. variolosus complex (D. specimen near C. brevipennis from Guerrero; E. specimen  CNCHB 1905 – 11 from Chiapas; F. specimen  CNCHB 1906 – 11 from Veracruz)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282462/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578CE9FAE2FD4AFACE" box="[640,656,1367,1391]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
), hump-backed, usually with long lateral margins of pronotum, and male anal tube with hoodlike articulated base (
<figureCitation id="1354EFE0FFEE37578CD1FACFFD24FA33" box="[696,766,1402,1426]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 15" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1877,1900]" captionTargetBox="[221,1369,524,1773]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[217,1369,519,1863]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 15. Male genitalia of Ptyelini in lateral aspect (A), caudal aspect of theca (B) and widest aspect of style (C). 5. genital capsule of Ptyelus; 6. same, of Cephisus; 7. syntype male of C. sanguisuga; 8. C. diminutus, holotype; 9. C. laticeps, holotype; 10. C. xanthocephala; 11. C. magnificus, holotype; 12. C. variolosus; 13. C. siccifolia; 14. C. jacobii; 15. C. brevipennis, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282464/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578C99FACFFD24FA33" box="[752,766,1402,1426]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
A) probably homologous with basal half of segment X in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6F88E6FFEE37578EFEFA2AFE98FA16" box="[151,322,1439,1463]" class="Insecta" family="Aphrophoridae" genus="Cnemidanomia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B91B2F77FFEE37578EFEFA2AFE98FA16" box="[151,322,1439,1463]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">Cnemidanomia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="1354EFE0FFEE37578F38FA2AFE7EFA16" box="[337,420,1439,1463]" captionStart="FIGURES 16 – 19" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[313,1267,498,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[313,1273,481,1921]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 16 – 19. Habitus of genera of Ptyelini (A), male genitalic capsule in lateral aspect (B) and male theca (C) in caudal aspect. 16. Mandesa; 17. Cnemidanomia; 18. Novaphrophara; 19. Hymettus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/282465/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="47">
Fig. 
<number id="3DA7E142FFEE37578FEFFA2AFE7EFA16" box="[390,420,1439,1463]" pageId="6" pageNumber="47" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
B).
</paragraph>
